Day 1: Species distribution models

Example of frequentist species distribution models

M. Grazia Pennino

1 Introduction

This practical section provides an introduction to species distribution modeling with R following the usual steps, such as: (1) compile locations of occurrence of a species; (2) extract values of environmental predictor variables at these locations from spatial databases; (3) use the environmental values to fit a model and to estimate the relationship among the species and its habitat; (4) extrapolate the identified relationship to predict the species distribution across a region of interest (and perhaps for a future or past climate); (5) validate the predictions. We will also see how produce psuedo-absence when are needed. SDM are implemented in R in many different ways. Here we focus on the functions in the dismo and the raster packages (but we also refer to other packages). Make sure you have the latest versions of these packages, and their dependencies, installed:

install.packages(c(name_library1, name_library1), dependencies = TRUE)

Then charge the libraries in a R section:

library(dismo)
library(spdep)
library(Hmisc)
library(raster)
library(GGally)
library(ggplot2)
library(corrplot)
library(maptools)
library(sdmpredictors)
library(PresenceAbsence)

2 Species occurrence data and data cleaning

In this practical section we use data of the Argentine hake (\(Merluccius\) \(hubbsi\)) species, which habitat is in the southwestern Atlantic Ocean, along the coast of Argentina. This dataset includes only-presence locations and were downloaded from the Ocean Biogeographic Information System (OBIS) (http://www.obis.org.au/cgi-bin/cs_map.pl). First we read the data in our workspace in R:

# Read data from csv file 
setwd("~/masterValencia/Day1/Practice")
data <- read.csv("data.csv")

#OR Rdata

load("data.RData")

This dataset has 3 columns. The first indicating the presence of the species (1) and the others two are coordinates of the locations in which the species was found present.

dim(data)
## [1] 260   3
head(data)
##   Species    Lat    Lon
## 1       1 -50.75 -62.25
## 2       1 -50.25 -68.25
## 3       1 -50.25 -62.75
## 4       1 -50.25 -62.75
## 5       1 -50.25 -61.75
## 6       1 -50.25 -61.25

Coordinates are typically expressed as longitude and latitude, but they could also be Easting and Northing with UTM or another planar coordinate reference system (map projection).
Check always the format before analysis the data.

The second step is always to map the data in order to assure that the points are, at least roughly, in the right location.

data(wrld_simpl)
plot(wrld_simpl, xlim=c(-80,70), ylim=c(-60,10), axes=TRUE,col="light yellow")
points(data$Lon, data$Lat, col="orange", pch=20, cex=0.75)
points(data$Lon, data$Lat, col="red", cex=0.75)

There are a few records that map in the Indian Ocean, close to Madagascar. Any idea why that may have happened? It is a common mistake, missing minus signs. The coordinates are around (50.78, -31.06) but they should in Brazil around (-50.78, -31.06).

You can use the click() function to query the coordinates on the map, or the identify(data\(Lon, data\)Lat)function to know the position of the erroneous locations in the dataset. So the latitude is probably correct, and erroneously copied to the longitude. In this case we eliminate these observations from the dataset but you can correct them.

data<-data[-c(259,260), ]

We plot again to be sure that we eliminate the data:

plot(wrld_simpl, xlim=c(-80,70), ylim=c(-60,10), axes=TRUE,col="light yellow")
points(data$Lon, data$Lat, col="orange", pch=20, cex=0.75)
points(data$Lon, data$Lat, col="red", cex=0.75)

Another common error is that some observations are duplicated. A good practice is to check if there are duplicated observations and correct the error:

dups2 <- duplicated(data[, c("Species","Lon","Lat")]);#which records are duplicates?

3 Environmental data

In SDMs predictor variables are typically organized as raster (grid) type files. Each predictor should be a \(raster\) representing a variable of interest. For any particular study the layers should all have the same spatial extent, resolution and projection. Using the library \(sdmpredictors\) we can easily check in R which variables you would like to use from different databases. Here we use some predictor from the Bio-ORCALE database that offers an array of geophysical, biotic and climate data at a spatial resolution 5 arcmin (9.2 km) in the ESRI ascii format.

6 Absence and background points

Some of the early species distribution model algorithms, such as BIOCLIM, only use presence data in the modeling process. Other methods also use absence data. One example is the logistic regression that is often implemented in a generalized linear modeling (GLM) framework. If you have a large dataset with presence/absence from a well-designed survey, you should use a method that can use these data (i.e.do not use a modeling method that only considers presence data). If you only have presence data, you can still use a method that needs absence data, by substituting absence data with background data. Background data establishes the environmental domain of the study, whilst presence data should establish under which conditions a species is more likely to be present than on average. In the example below, we use the rasterStack object predictors as background. Using the randomPoints() function we sample 200 locations from the background that will be used as absence locations.

set.seed(500)
backgr <- randomPoints(predictors2, 200)

7 Exploration of the dataset

Before run any SDMs a good practice is to perform some explanatory analysis on the collinearity, correlation and linearity of the explicative variables with respect to the response one. We can use different approach. One for example is to compute a correlation matrix and plot it with the corrplot() function also assessing which correlation are significant or not

7.1 Step 1: Check correlation among explicative variables. Variables highly correlated can NOT be used together in the model.

M=cor(sdmdata[,c(1:9)])
testRes = cor.mtest(sdmdata[,c(1:9)], conf.level = 0.95)

#specialized the insignificant value according to the significant level
corrplot(M,  order = 'hclust', addrect = 2)

#If using 'hclust', corrplot() can draw rectangles around the plot of correlation matrix based on the results of hierarchical clustering

7.2 Step 2: Check if the response variables and the explicative variables have linear relationship

my_fn <- function(data, mapping, ...){
  p <- ggplot(data = data, mapping = mapping) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method=loess, fill="red", color="red", ...) +
    geom_smooth(method=lm, fill="blue", color="blue", ...)
  p
}

g = ggpairs(sdmdata[,c(1:9)], lower = list(continuous = my_fn))
g

7.3 Step 3: Check multicollinearity among variables

Collinearity among explanatory variables, can complicate or prevent the identification of an optimal set of explanatory variables for a statistical model. Here, we use a simple approach to identify collinearity among explanatory variables using the variance inflation factors (VIF). VIF calculations are straightforward and easily comprehensible; the higher the value, the higher the collinearity. A VIF is calculated for each explanatory variable and those with high values are removed. The definition of high is somewhat arbitrary but values higher than 5 have to be removed.

setwd("~/masterValencia/Day1/Practice")

8 Generalized Linear Models (GLMs)

Now we have a dataset of presence/absence so we can use different models. Here we use a generalized linear model (GLM), which is a generalization of ordinary least squares regression. Models are fit using maximum likelihood and by allowing the linear model to be related to the response variable via a link function. Specifically, we use a binomial distribution (as our response variables is binary 1 and 0) with the common logit link function. In R, GLM is implemented in the glm() function, and the link function and error distribution are specified with the family argument (family = binomial(link = logit)).

m1<- glm(pb ~ calcite+chlomean+nitrate+ph+salinity, data=sdmdata,family="binomial")
summary(m1)

9 Model evaluation

Model evaluation is needed to verify how good the prediction is. The easier way is to see the correlation among the predicted and the observed occurrence:

coords<-as.data.frame(cbind(sdmdata$x,sdmdata$y))
pp<-extract(pglm,coords)
pp<-as.data.frame(pp)
sdmdata<-cbind(sdmdata,pp)
sdmdata<-na.omit(sdmdata)
cor(sdmdata$pp,sdmdata$pb,method="spearman")
## [1] 0.7616233

In this case is about 0.76 that is quite good.

A common procedure to evaluate the prediction is the cross-validation. This process consists in split randomly the dataset in two main sub-sets, a training dataset (that usually includes the 70-80% of the observations) and the validation dataset (which includes the remaining 30-20%). Then the training dataset is used to run the model again and find the relationship between the species occurrence and the environmental variables, while the validation dataset is used to verify how much of the predicted presence and absences were really observed. This procedure is repeated multiple times and results are averaged over the different random subsets. Here we use the sample() function to generate these subsets and we use the proportions of 80-20%.

set.seed(600)
samp <- sample(nrow(sdmdata), round(0.80 * nrow(sdmdata)))
traindata <- sdmdata[samp,]
testdata <- sdmdata[-samp,]
m<- glm(pb ~ calcite+chlomean+nitrate+ph+salinity, data=sdmdata,family="binomial")
pglm1<-predict(predictors2,m,type='response')
plot(pglm1)
plot(wrld_simpl, add=TRUE, col="grey")
points(testdata$x,testdata$y,col=testdata$pb+1, pch=16,cex=.70)

Different measures can be used to evaluate the quality of a prediction. Many measures for evaluating models based on presence-absence or presence-only data are threshold dependent. That means that a threshold must be set first. Predicted values above that threshold indicate a prediction of presence, and values below the threshold indicate absence. Some measures emphasize the weight of false absences; others give more weight to false presences.

Much used statistics that are threshold independent are the correlation coefficient and the Area Under the Receiver Operator Curve (generally further abbreviated to AUC). AUC is a measure of rank-correlation. In unbiased data, a high AUC indicates that sites with high-predicted suitability values tend to be areas of known presence and locations with lower model prediction values tend to be areas where the species is not known to be present (absent or a random point). AUC score of 0.5 means that the model is as good as a random guess. Here we illustrate the computation of these measure using the evaluate() function:

eglm <- dismo::evaluate(testdata[testdata==1,], testdata[testdata==0,], m);eglm
## class          : ModelEvaluation 
## n presences    : 50 
## n absences     : 41 
## AUC            : 0.9619512 
## cor            : 0.6771779 
## max TPR+TNR at : 0.1591739
plot(eglm, "ROC")

We can also compute the True Skill Statistic values (TSS) indicator. It deals with sensitivity and specificity, values ranging from 1 to + 1, where + 1 indicates perfect agreement, scores ranging from 0.6 to 0.9 specify fair to good model performance, and 0 represents a random fit.

TSSglm <- mean(eglm@TPR+eglm@TNR-1);TSSglm
## [1] 0.4517545

We can compute the threshold using the threshold() function in R:

tr <- threshold(eglm,"spec_sens");tr
## [1] 0.1591739

Using the find threshold we can plot a binary map only with presence and absence and not probabilities:

plot(pglm1 > tr, main = "presence/absence")
plot(wrld_simpl, add=TRUE, col= "grey") 
points(traindata$x,traindata$y, col =traindata$pb+1, pch=16, cex=.70)

9.1 Spatial autocorrelation

A common problem in the model that not takes into account the spatial component is the spatial autocorrelation. Lets verify if our model and predictions have this problem. The easiest way to evaluate this assumption is to plot the model residuals by their spatial coordinates. We would expect to see some spatial pattern in the residuals if we have not accounted for spatial correlation. We use the bubble() plot function:

dat<-data.frame(coords, resids=resid(m1)) 
colnames(dat)<-c("x","y","resids") 
coordinates(dat)<-c('x','y');
bubble(dat, zcol='resids')

A nice feature of the bubble function is that it colors codes the residuals based on positive and negative values and sets the size of the points in proportion to the magnitude. An examination of the plot shows a clear residual pattern with longitude such that smaller values are seen towards the east. The bubble plot provides a qualitative means of evaluating spatial correlation We can also apply a statistical test to verify if there is spatial autocorrelation.

The Morans I is a measure of spatial autocorrelationhow related the values of a variable are based on the locations where they were measured. To calculate Morans I, we will need to generate a matrix of distance weights. Using the latitude and longitude values:

nb <- dnearneigh(as.matrix(coords), 1,8);nb
## Neighbour list object:
## Number of regions: 456 
## Number of nonzero links: 60524 
## Percentage nonzero weights: 29.10703 
## Average number of links: 132.7281
plot(wrld_simpl, xlim=c(-70,-30), ylim=c(-55,-20), axes=TRUE,col="light yellow")
plot(nb, coords, col='red', lwd=2, add=TRUE)

listw <- nb2listw(nb,style = "S")#turns neighbourhood object into a weighted list

Here the style S compute the variance stabilization (Tiefelsdorf et al.1999) You can also use:

W = row standardized (rows sum to 1), Emphasizes weakly connected points B = binary (0/1), Emphasizes strongly connected points C = global standardized (all links sum to n), Emphasizes strongly connected points

The null hypothesis of this test is that there is no spatial autocorrelation. Then with p-values less than (0.05) the null hypothesis has to be rejected:

MoranI <- moran.test(residuals(m1), listw=listw, randomisation=FALSE); 
MoranI
## 
##  Moran I test under normality
## 
## data:  residuals(m1)  
## weights: listw    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 9.5352, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      4.486834e-02     -2.197802e-03      2.436467e-05

We can conclude that there is spatial autocorrelation.
